        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(gmail): detect HTML fragments in LooksLikeHTML to prevent signature escaping",
        "body": "## What\n\n`LooksLikeHTML` only detected document-level HTML (`<!doctype>`, `<html>`, `<head>`, `<body>`, `<meta>`). When `--signature-file` pointed at a file starting with `<style>` or `<table>` — common in HTML email signatures — it failed detection and fell through to `escapeTextToHTML`, which HTML-escaped the entire signature. Recipients saw `&lt;style&gt;` and `&lt;table&gt;` as visible text instead of rendered HTML.\n\n## Why\n\n`readComposeSignatureFile` in `internal/cmd/gmail_send_signature.go:85` calls `LooksLikeHTML` to decide whether to preserve raw HTML or escape it. A `<style>`-prefixed signature file is valid HTML but not a full document, so it was misclassified as plain text and escaped.\n\nA broader `looksLikeHTMLFragment` already exists in `internal/cmd/backup_export_gmail.go:244` with the right marker list (`<style`, `<table`, `<div`, `<p`, `<br`, etc.). This PR extends `LooksLikeHTML` with the same markers so the signature path — and any other caller of `LooksLikeHTML` — correctly detects HTML fragments.\n\n## Tests\n\n```bash\ngo test ./internal/gmailcontent/ -run TestLooksLikeHTML -v\n```\n\n- `TestLooksLikeHTML_DocumentPrefixes` — existing document-level detection unchanged\n- `TestLooksLikeHTML_FragmentMarkers` — `<style>`, `<table>`, `<div>`, `<p>`, `<br>`, `<span>`, `<section>`, `<blockquote>`, `<a>`, `<img>`, `<font>`, `<!--` all detected as HTML\n- `TestLooksLikeHTML_PlainText` — plain text, bare URLs, `a < b` not misdetected as HTML\n\nAlso verified via integration test: `readComposeSignatureFile` with a `<style>`-prefixed file now returns raw HTML (not escaped) in the `composeSignature.HTML` field.\n\n## AI Assistance\n\nThis PR was authored with AI assistance (Claude Code / OpenCode + GLM 5.2). The bug was discovered when an OpenClaw agent sent a BIPA legal acknowledgement email to counsel at GRSM and the HTML signature was delivered as escaped visible text. Root cause traced through the raw RFC822 message to `html.EscapeString` output matching exactly.",
